    "review::.::holistic::convention_outlier::season_script_protocol_drift::0e83333e": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::convention_outlier::season_script_protocol_drift::0e83333e",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 2,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "Sibling season calculators use different internal protocols for the same WMI workflow",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "convention_outlier",
        "related_files": [
          "calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py",
          "calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py",
          "calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py",
          "build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py` centers its workflow on `build_possession_table_for_game()` and a per-game table with `L_t/F_t/N_t/M_t`, matching the raw-game script's column contract.",
          "`calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py` computes the same season metric through a different protocol: `build_foul_vector()` and `game_wmi_components()` work directly on action arrays and never reuse the same table-building contract.",
          "Network helper naming and behavior also drift across these sibling modules (`fetch_status`, `fetch_game_json_with_retry`, `fetch_json_with_retry`), which makes the season scripts feel like separate style islands rather than one family of tools."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Define one canonical pipeline for WMI computation, such as `actions -> possession table -> WMI aggregates`, and have both season scripts use the same helper names and intermediate contract. Shared fetch/parsing helpers should live in one module with one naming scheme.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
